As political parties begin the conduct of their primaries, a financial expert and one-time chief economic adviser to Abia State Government, Dr. Agu Ojukwu, has tasked delegates in all the political parties to nominate techno­crats to oversee the Nigerian economy. Briefing newsmen in Umuahia, Ojukwu, who is also a strategic manager and development expert, remind­ed delegates in the current party primaries that whoev­er they nominate would even­tually be chosen by the elec­torate during the elections, warning that if they choose the wrong candidates, the electorates would also elect from that pool. In his speech which he ti­tled ‘Advocacy to elect candi­dates who are likely to use the collective wisdom of the peo­ple (not just theirs) to lead’, the former economic adviser to the then administration of Theodore Orji, lamented that no administration in Nigeria had developed a concept for development since the col­lapse of the First Republic. -Advertisement- “As a crusader and advo­cate for rapid economic and social development, there comes a time in the life of the strategic management/ organization development consultant and change agent when he must become an ac­tivist or deepen his activism to awaken the consciousness of the people to what is right to do. “Nigeria is embarking on make or break 2023 general elections. Presidential and gubernatorial aspirants are already talking about how they will fix the economy in four to eight years, a pro­gramme which successive ad­ministrations since the civil war ended undertook under various titles with limited success.